                    <span>Before I read this book I liked Namath. I've seen him play at Alabama. After reading it I see him as selfish, money hungry drunk. The book is good, Namath is not.
<br />AW  Moble, Alabama</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A fun read.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-15</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This book is a biography of Joe Namath and starts out from his birth and follows the course of his life through high school, college, professional football, and thereafter. It gives an inside look at what type of person Joe Namath really is, and provides much insight into the personality of a very unique individual. The book gives many stories of life on the football field and off of it. I thought the stories of Namath's very fast paced life living in New York was the best part. I was a little surpirised that he was basically dumped by his wife and while he had many friends, he appears to have struggled with developing lasting and intimate friendships.
<br />Whether you are a football fan or not, this book is a great read, especially if you grew up in the 1960's and 1970's time era. I would highly recommend it.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Great Athlete, Almost Great Book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-11</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Joe Namath was a childhood idol of mine.  Kriegel captures very well what a great athlete he was and how he truly was the first of the new breed of made-for-TV sports stars.  The book is very insightful about Joe's early years through the end of his professional playing days.  I would have liked to have known a little more about his personal life since his football career ended, but maybe there just isn't that much to say.  My two complaints are that the writing is sometimes overblown and in many places there is too much detail.  We know he was a swinger and a drinker, how many times need we be reminded?</span>
                  
              
